{
  "In Principal Component Analysis (PCA), the first principal component is the direction of:": "",
  "Maximum variance in the data": "",
  "Minimum variance in the data": "",
  "Zero variance in the data": "",
  "Average variance in the data": "",
  "The first principal component is the unit vector along which the projected data has the greatest variance. It captures the most information (spread) in the data. Mathematically, it is the eigenvector of the covariance matrix corresponding to the largest eigenvalue.": "",
  "In a linear regression model y = Xb + e, the least squares solution minimizes which quantity?": "",
  "The rank of X": "",
  "The sum of the residuals": "",
  "The determinant of X": "",
  "The sum of squared residuals ||y - Xb||^2": "",
  "The ordinary least squares (OLS) solution finds the coefficient vector b that minimizes the sum of squared residuals ||y - Xb||^2. The solution is b = (X^T X)^(-1) X^T y when X has full column rank.": "",
  "What does the rank of a data matrix X (n samples by p features) tell us about the data?": "",
  "The total variance in the data as typically measured in practice": "",
  "The average of all entries when applying fundamental principles": "",
  "The number of linearly independent features (or samples, whichever is smaller)": "",
  "The number of samples, particularly regarding matrix in the": "",
  "The rank of the data matrix equals the number of linearly independent columns (features), which also equals the number of linearly independent rows. It tells us the intrinsic dimensionality of the data and is at most min(n, p).": "",
  "What is the covariance matrix of a centered data matrix X?": "",
  "X + X^T": "",
  "(1/(n-1)) * X^T X": "",
  "The inverse of X": "",
  "X * X": "",
  "For a centered data matrix X (columns have mean zero) with n samples as rows, the sample covariance matrix is S = (1/(n-1)) * X^T X. It is a p x p symmetric positive semi-definite matrix whose diagonal entries are the variances of each feature.": "",
  "If a dataset in R^10 lies approximately on a 3-dimensional subspace, how many principal components are needed to capture most of the variance?": "",
  "10": "",
  "1": "",
  "7": "",
  "3": "",
  "If the data lies approximately on a 3-dimensional subspace, then the first 3 principal components will capture most of the variance. The remaining 7 components correspond to small eigenvalues (little variance) and can be discarded for dimensionality reduction.": "",
  "In the Singular Value Decomposition (SVD) A = U * Sigma * V^T, what are the columns of V?": "",
  "The eigenvalues of A": "",
  "The left singular vectors": "",
  "The right singular vectors (principal directions of A^T A)": "",
  "The singular values": "",
  "In the SVD A = U * Sigma * V^T, the columns of V are the right singular vectors, which are the eigenvectors of A^T A. In data science contexts (A is a data matrix), these are the principal component directions.": "",
  "What does 'dimensionality reduction' mean in data science?": "",
  "Reducing the number of features while preserving important structure in the data": "",
  "Normalizing all features to unit variance": "",
  "Converting data to binary format": "",
  "Removing data samples": "",
  "Dimensionality reduction projects high-dimensional data onto a lower-dimensional subspace while retaining as much relevant information as possible. PCA, SVD-based methods, and other techniques find the optimal subspace for this projection.": "",
  "The normal equation for least squares regression is:": "",
  "X^T X b = X^T y": "",
  "b = X / y": "",
  "X^T b = y": "",
  "Xb = y": "",
  "The normal equation X^T X b = X^T y is derived by setting the gradient of ||y - Xb||^2 to zero. Multiplying both sides of Xb approximately equals y by X^T projects onto the column space of X. If X^T X is invertible, b = (X^T X)^(-1) X^T y.": "",
  "In a recommender system, the user-item rating matrix R (m users by n items) is approximated as R approximately equals U * V^T, where U is m x k and V is n x k. What does k represent?": "",
  "The number of items": "",
  "The number of latent factors (rank of the approximation)": "",
  "The number of users": "",
  "The number of ratings": "",
  "In low-rank matrix factorization for recommender systems, k is the number of latent factors. Each user is represented by a k-dimensional vector (row of U) and each item by a k-dimensional vector (row of V). The inner product approximates the rating.": "",
  "What does it mean for features to be 'multicollinear' in a regression model?": "",
  "Features have different variances": "",
  "Two or more feature columns are approximately linearly dependent": "",
  "Features are measured in different units": "",
  "Features are stored in multiple columns": "",
  "Multicollinearity occurs when two or more feature columns are approximately linearly dependent (one can be nearly predicted from the others). This makes X^T X nearly singular, leading to unstable and unreliable coefficient estimates in regression.": "",
  "What is 'Principal Component Analysis' (PCA)?": "",
  "A method for computing the determinant of a matrix": "",
  "A classification algorithm for labeled data": "",
  "A technique for handling missing values": "",
  "A dimensionality reduction technique that finds orthogonal directions of maximum variance in the data": "",
  "PCA is a technique that transforms data into a new coordinate system where the axes (principal components) are orthogonal directions ordered by decreasing variance. It is used for dimensionality reduction, visualization, and noise reduction by keeping only the top components.": "",
  "What is 'Singular Value Decomposition' (SVD)?": "",
  "A method for computing the inverse of any matrix": "",
  "A factorization of any matrix A into A = U * Sigma * V^T where U and V are orthogonal and Sigma is diagonal": "",
  "A technique that only works on square matrices": "",
  "The process of removing singular points from a dataset": "",
  "The SVD decomposes any m x n matrix A into U * Sigma * V^T, where U (m x m) and V (n x n) are orthogonal matrices and Sigma (m x n) is a diagonal matrix of non-negative singular values. It exists for every matrix and is fundamental in data science.": "",
  "What is 'low-rank approximation' of a matrix?": "",
  "Computing the rank of a matrix, particularly regarding theorem within the typical range of values": "",
  "Approximating a matrix by another matrix of lower rank, retaining only the most significant singular values/vectors": "",
  "Replacing all small entries with zero as determined by standard methodology": "",
  "Reducing the number of rows in a matrix based on established principles": "",
  "Low-rank approximation replaces a matrix A with a rank-k matrix A_k (where k < rank(A)) that is as close to A as possible. Using SVD, A_k is obtained by keeping only the k largest singular values. The Eckart-Young theorem proves this is optimal in the Frobenius and spectral norms.": "",
  "What is the 'least squares projection' in linear algebra?": "",
  "Finding the eigenvalues of the projection matrix": "",
  "Projecting a vector onto the null space of a matrix": "",
  "Projecting a vector b onto the column space of A to find the closest vector Ax to b": "",
  "Reducing all coordinates to their squares": "",
  "The least squares projection finds the vector in Col(A) closest to b. This projected vector is p = A * (A^T A)^(-1) * A^T * b, and the projection matrix is P = A(A^T A)^(-1)A^T. The residual b - p is orthogonal to Col(A).": "",
  "What does 'explained variance ratio' mean in PCA?": "",
  "The R-squared value of the regression, particularly regarding explained when evaluated systematically": "",
  "The variance of the explained variables when applying fundamental principles": "",
  "The proportion of total variance in the data captured by each principal component (eigenvalue divided by sum of all eigenvalues)": "",
  "The ratio of features to samples, particularly regarding ratio in most standard conditions": "",
  "The explained variance ratio for the i-th principal component is lambda_i / (lambda_1 + lambda_2 + ... + lambda_p), where lambda_i is the i-th eigenvalue of the covariance matrix. It tells you what fraction of total data variance is captured by that component.": "",
  "What is 'matrix factorization' in the context of recommender systems?": "",
  "Removing duplicate rows from the matrix": "",
  "Splitting a database into multiple tables": "",
  "Computing the prime factors of matrix entries": "",
  "Decomposing a rating matrix into the product of lower-dimensional user and item factor matrices to predict missing ratings": "",
  "Matrix factorization in recommender systems decomposes the sparse user-item rating matrix R into R approximately equal to U * V^T, where U contains user latent factors and V contains item latent factors. Missing ratings are predicted by computing the corresponding entries of U * V^T.": "",
  "What does 'feature extraction' mean using linear algebra?": "",
  "Sorting features by alphabetical order, particularly regarding feature under equilibrium conditions": "",
  "Removing features with missing values, particularly regarding linear under normal circumstances": "",
  "Manually selecting columns from a spreadsheet as determined by standard methodology": "",
  "Creating new features by projecting data onto a lower-dimensional subspace defined by important directions (e.g., principal components)": "",
  "Feature extraction constructs new features as linear combinations of the original features. PCA is a prime example: the new features are projections onto principal component directions. These extracted features are often more informative and lower-dimensional than the originals.": "",
  "What is 'latent semantic analysis' (LSA)?": "",
  "A grammar-checking algorithm, particularly regarding where based on the prevailing evidence": "",
  "A method for translating between languages when applying fundamental principles": "",
  "A technique for counting word frequencies under equilibrium conditions": "",
  "An application of SVD to a term-document matrix to discover hidden (latent) semantic relationships between words and documents": "",
  "LSA applies SVD to a term-document matrix (where entry (i,j) represents the frequency of term i in document j). The low-rank approximation reveals latent semantic structure, allowing documents with similar meanings (but different words) to be identified as related.": "",
  "What does 'orthogonal projection' mean in the context of data science?": "",
  "Projecting data points at right angles onto a subspace, minimizing the perpendicular distance from each point to the subspace": "",
  "Rotating data so all features are uncorrelated based on the prevailing evidence": "",
  "Removing outliers from the dataset, particularly regarding perpendicular as determined by standard methodology": "",
  "Making all features orthogonal to each other when applying fundamental principles": "",
  "Orthogonal projection maps each data point to the nearest point in a subspace. The projection is perpendicular (orthogonal) to the subspace, meaning the residual (difference between original and projected point) is orthogonal to the subspace. PCA uses orthogonal projection onto the top principal component subspace.": "",
  "What is the 'pseudoinverse' (Moore-Penrose inverse) of a matrix?": "",
  "A generalization of the matrix inverse that exists for any matrix (including non-square and singular matrices) and provides the least squares solution": "",
  "The inverse of the transpose, particularly regarding inverts in accordance with classical theory": "",
  "The negative of the inverse, particularly regarding what based on established principles": "",
  "A fake inverse that does not actually work, particularly regarding gives within the typical range of values": "",
  "The pseudoinverse A^+ generalizes the inverse to any matrix. For Ax = b, x = A^+ * b gives the least squares solution with minimum norm. Using SVD, if A = U * Sigma * V^T, then A^+ = V * Sigma^+ * U^T, where Sigma^+ inverts the nonzero singular values.": "",
  "A streaming service has a 10000-user by 5000-movie rating matrix with many missing entries. They use matrix factorization with rank k = 20 to predict missing ratings. How many parameters does the model have?": "",
  "20": "",
  "15,000 (10000 + 5000)": "",
  "300,000 (10000 x 20 + 5000 x 20)": "",
  "50,000,000 (10000 x 5000)": "",
  "The factorization R approximately equal to U * V^T has U as 10000 x 20 (200,000 parameters) and V as 5000 x 20 (100,000 parameters), for a total of 300,000 parameters. This is far fewer than the 50,000,000 entries in the full matrix, making the model efficient.": "",
  "A data scientist has a dataset with 1000 samples and 50 features. She runs PCA and finds that the first 5 eigenvalues account for 95% of the total variance. She decides to project the data onto 5 principal components. What is the shape of the transformed dataset?": "",
  "1000 x 50": "",
  "50 x 5": "",
