  "A search engine uses LSA to find documents similar to a query. The term-document matrix is 10000 terms by 100000 documents. Computing a rank-200 SVD approximation, the search engine represents each document as a vector in what dimensional space?": "",
  "10,000-dimensional": "",
  "100,000-dimensional": "",
  "200-dimensional": "",
  "20-dimensional": "",
  "A rank-200 SVD reduces the representation to 200 dimensions. Each document is represented by a 200-dimensional vector (from the columns of V scaled by singular values, or the columns of U * Sigma). Similarity between documents can then be computed efficiently in this 200-dimensional space.": "",
  "A medical researcher has patient data with 100 features but suspects many are redundant. She computes the covariance matrix and finds that 90 eigenvalues are nearly zero. How many effective degrees of freedom does the data have?": "",
  "50": "",
  "90": "",
  "100": "",
  "If 90 out of 100 eigenvalues are nearly zero, the data effectively lives in a 10-dimensional subspace (the directions corresponding to the 10 significant eigenvalues). The data has approximately 10 effective degrees of freedom, and 90 features are essentially redundant.": "",
  "A machine learning engineer trains a linear regression model with 20 features but only 15 training samples. He finds that X^T X is singular. What is the issue and what can he do?": "",
  "This cannot happen in practice, particularly regarding finds based on the prevailing evidence": "",
  "The model has too few features; add more, particularly regarding solution according to conventional analysis": "",
  "With more features than samples, X^T X is singular (underdetermined system); he should use regularization (e.g., ridge regression) or reduce dimensions": "",
  "The data has errors; re-collect it, particularly regarding invertible when considering all relevant factors": "",
  "When p > n (more features than samples), rank(X) <= n < p, so X^T X (p x p) is singular and the normal equation has infinitely many solutions. Ridge regression adds a regularization term (X^T X + lambda * I)b = X^T y, making the matrix invertible and selecting a unique, stable solution.": "",
  "An image compression algorithm uses SVD on a 1000x1000 grayscale image matrix. Using a rank-50 approximation, how many values need to be stored instead of the original 1,000,000?": "",
