  "Two distinct clusters in the PCA plot indicate that the largest sources of gene expression variation separate patients into two groups. These may correspond to different disease subtypes, treatment responses, or other biological categories. PCA reveals this structure by finding the most informative low-dimensional projection.": "",
  "A retail company wants to predict sales (y) using 8 economic indicators (features). They fit y = Xb using least squares and get a coefficient vector b. They then discover that two features are nearly perfectly correlated (correlation 0.99). What problem does this cause and what is the linear algebra explanation?": "",
  "X^T X is nearly singular (ill-conditioned), making the coefficients b highly sensitive to small changes in data (multicollinearity)": "",
  "The residuals become negative, particularly regarding perfect as typically measured in practice": "",
  "The model underfits because of too few features within the typical range of values": "",
  "No problem; high correlation improves predictions as predicted by standard models": "",
  "Near-perfect correlation between two features means their column vectors are nearly linearly dependent, making X^T X nearly singular (one eigenvalue is near zero). The condition number is large, causing the least squares solution to be numerically unstable. Small data perturbations lead to wildly different coefficient estimates. Solutions include dropping one feature, using PCA, or applying ridge regression.": ""
